body:
# Notion Databases

Databases are structured collections of pages in Notion. Each database defines a property schema, and every page (row) in the database has values for those properties. The Databases API supports creating databases, querying with compound filters and sorts, retrieving schema information, and updating database properties.

## Create

Create a database with POST to `/v1/databases` specifying a `parent` (page ID), `title`, and `properties` schema.

```javascript
const { Client } = require('@notionhq/client');
const notion = new Client({ auth: process.env.NOTION_TOKEN });

const database = await notion.databases.create({
  parent: { page_id: parentPageId },
  title: [{ text: { content: 'Project Tracker' } }],
  properties: {
    Name: { title: {} },
    Status: {
      select: {
        options: [
          { name: 'Not Started', color: 'gray' },
          { name: 'In Progress', color: 'blue' },
          { name: 'Done', color: 'green' }
        ]
      }
    },
    Priority: { number: { format: 'number' } },
    'Due Date': { date: {} }
  }
});
```

## Query with Filters

Query a database with POST to `/v1/databases/{id}/query`. Filters support compound logic with `and`, `or`, and nested conditions.

```javascript
const results = await notion.databases.query({
  database_id: databaseId,
  filter: {
    and: [
      {
        property: 'Status',
        select: { equals: 'In Progress' }
      },
      {
        property: 'Priority',
        number: { greater_than: 3 }
      }
    ]
  },
  sorts: [
    { property: 'Priority', direction: 'descending' },
    { property: 'Due Date', direction: 'ascending' }
  ],
  page_size: 50
});
```

## Sort

Sorts are an ordered array of sort objects. Each specifies a `property` name and `direction` (`ascending` or `descending`). You can also sort by `timestamp` (`created_time` or `last_edited_time`). Multiple sorts are applied in order.

## Property Types

Database schema properties define what data each page can hold:

| Type | Filter Operators | Description |
|------|-----------------|-------------|
| Title | equals, contains, starts_with, is_empty | Page name |
| Rich text | equals, contains, starts_with, is_empty | Free-form text |
| Number | equals, greater_than, less_than, is_empty | Numeric values |
| Select | equals, does_not_equal, is_empty | Single dropdown |
| Multi-select | contains, does_not_contain, is_empty | Multiple tags |
| Date | equals, before, after, on_or_before, on_or_after, is_empty | Date or date range |
| Checkbox | equals | Boolean true/false |
| URL | equals, contains, is_empty | Web links |
| Relation | contains, does_not_contain, is_empty | Cross-database references |
| Formula | Depends on result type | Computed values |
| Rollup | Depends on rollup type | Aggregated relation data |

## Pagination

Query results are paginated. The response includes `has_more` (boolean) and `next_cursor` (string). Pass `start_cursor` in subsequent requests to fetch the next page. Maximum `page_size` is 100.

```javascript
let allResults = [];
let cursor = undefined;

do {
  const response = await notion.databases.query({
    database_id: databaseId,
    start_cursor: cursor,
    page_size: 100
  });
  allResults.push(...response.results);
  cursor = response.has_more ? response.next_cursor : undefined;
} while (cursor);
```
